\hypertarget{expressjs}{%
\subsection{2. ExpressJS}\label{expressjs}}

\hypertarget{what-is-expressjs}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.1 What is ExpressJS
?}}{2.1 What is ExpressJS ?}}\label{what-is-expressjs}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  ExpressJS is a web application framework that provides you with a
  simple API to build websites, web apps and back ends. With ExpressJS,
  you need not worry about low level protocols, processes, etc.
\item
  Express provides a minimal interface to build our applications. It
  provides us the tools that are required to build our app. It is
  flexible as there are numerous modules available on npm, which can be
  directly plugged into Express.
\item
  Express was developed by TJ Holowaychuk and is maintained by the
  Node.js foundation and numerous open source contributors.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{why-express}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.2 Why Express
?}}{2.2 Why Express ?}}\label{why-express}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Unlike its competitors like Rails and Django, which have an
  opinionated way of building applications, Express has no "best way" to
  do something. It is very flexible and pluggable.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{mongodb-and-mongoose}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.3 MongoDB and
Mongoose}}{2.3 MongoDB and Mongoose}}\label{mongodb-and-mongoose}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  MongoDB is an open-source, document database designed for ease of
  development and scaling. This database is also used to store data.
\item
  Mongoose is a client API for node.js which makes it easy to access our
  database from our Express application
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{mongodb-overview}{%
\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{\textbf{2.4 MongoDB
Overview}}{2.4 MongoDB Overview}}\label{mongodb-overview}}

\hypertarget{what-is-mongodb}{%
\section{2.4.1 What is MongoDB ?}\label{what-is-mongodb}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  MongoDB is a cross-platform, document oriented database that provides,
  high performance, high availability, and easy scalability. MongoDB
  works on concept of collection and document.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{database}{%
\section{2.4.2 Database}\label{database}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Database is a physical container for collections. Each database gets
  its own set of files on the file system. A single MongoDB server
  typically has multiple databases.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{collection}{%
\section{2.4.3 Collection}\label{collection}}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Collection is a group of MongoDB documents. It is the equivalent of an
  RDBMS table. A collection exists within a single database. Collections
  do not enforce a schema. Documents within a collection can have
  different fields. Typically, all documents in a collection are of
  similar or related purpose.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{document}{%
\section{2.4.4 Document}\label{document}}

A document is a set of key-value pairs. Documents have dynamic schema.
Dynamic schema means that documents in the same collection do not need
to have the same set of fields or structure, and common fields in a
collection's documents may hold different types of data.

